{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "IsentropicBaseState",
        "description": "Isentropic base-state atmosphere for the Clark (1977) terrain-following mountain-wave model, \"A Small-Scale Dynamic Model Using a Terrain-Following Coordinate Transformation\", Eqs. 2.6-2.9. The base state assumes a constant potential temperature Θ — the deep, isentropic reference atmosphere of Ogura and Phillips (1962) adopted in Clark (1977) Eq. 2.6 — and derives the height-dependent thermodynamic profiles that satisfy hydrostatic balance: from the reference potential temperature Θ, the surface pressure P_0, and the height above the surface z, the component computes the isentropic scale height H_s = c_p*Θ/g, the base-state temperature T_bar = Θ*(1 - z/H_s) (Eq. 2.7), the base-state pressure p_bar = P_0*(1 - z/H_s)^(c_p/R_d) (Eq. 2.8), and the base-state density ρ_bar = P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(1 - z/H_s)^(c_p/R_d - 1) (Eq. 2.9). Temperature falls linearly with height while pressure and density fall as powers of the same (1 - z/H_s) factor, all three vanishing at the top of the isentropic atmosphere z = H_s. Four purely-algebraic equations, no time integration. Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/clark1977.jl:49 (`IsentropicBaseState` @component); the five upstream @constants — g, R_d, c_p and the derived exponents inv_kappa = c_p/R_d and inv_kappa_m1 = c_p/R_d - 1 — are declared as fixed-default parameters.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "clark-1977",
            "mountain-wave",
            "base-state",
            "isentropic-atmosphere",
            "hydrostatic-balance",
            "observed-only"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-dx08)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Clark, T. L. (1977). A Small-Scale Dynamic Model Using a Terrain-Following Coordinate Transformation. Journal of Computational Physics, 24(2), 186-215 — Section 2, Eqs. 2.6-2.9 (the isentropic base-state atmosphere) and Eq. 2.12 (the hydrostatic balance the profiles satisfy)."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Ogura, Y., and Phillips, N. A. (1962). Scale Analysis of Deep and Shallow Convection in the Atmosphere. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 19(2), 173-179 — origin of the deep, isentropic (constant potential temperature) base-state equations adopted in Clark (1977) Eq. 2.6."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "IsentropicBaseState": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Clark, T. L. (1977), J. Comput. Phys. 24(2), 186-215, Eqs. 2.6-2.9.",
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc3918e1eef2c2ee6d8fa8dd73c8f13a85a47:src/clark1977.jl:49\n\nUpstream `IsentropicBaseState` is a ModelingToolkit `@component` returning `System(eqs, t; name)` that implements the isentropic base-state atmosphere of Clark (1977), Sec. 2 — the constant-potential-temperature reference state (Eqs. 2.6-2.9) underlying the paper's mountain-wave model. It is one of the building-block components of the full `Clark1977AnelasticSystem`. All four equations are algebraic — there is no ODE integration and no `D(.)` operator.\n\nSystem classification. The upstream test `IsentropicBaseState Structure` (test/clark1977_test.jl:22-27) asserts `length(unknowns(bs)) == 4` and `length(equations(bs)) == 4`. The .esm preserves this exactly: four `type: state` variables (T_bar, p_bar, ρ_bar, H_s) and four entries in `equations`. Each equation is an explicit algebraic assignment — H_s depends only on parameters; T_bar, p_bar and ρ_bar each depend on parameters and the previously-defined H_s — so the four equations form an explicit cascade with no implicit/coupled solve. After `mtkcompile` they resolve to observed quantities and the compiled system has zero differential states, exactly as for the sibling explicit-algebraic components diagnostic_pressure.esm and anelastic_thermo.esm. The migration therefore leaves `system_kind` unset (default 'ode'); this is deliberately NOT the `system_kind: nonlinear` class, which is reserved for components needing an implicit Newton solve with initial guesses.\n\nConstants → parameters. The upstream component declares two symbol blocks: an `@constants` block (g, R_d, c_p, inv_kappa, inv_kappa_m1) and an `@parameters` block (Θ, P_0, z). The .esm schema has no dedicated constant variable type, so all eight symbols are encoded `type: parameter` with their upstream defaults — the same treatment the sibling diagnostic_pressure.esm applies to its `@constant g`. inv_kappa and inv_kappa_m1 are derived constants: upstream they are defined symbolically as `inv_kappa = c_p / R_d` and `inv_kappa_m1 = c_p / R_d - 1.0`. Their `default` fields here carry the evaluated IEEE-754 double values 3.4982578397212545 (= 1004.0/287.0) and 2.4982578397212545 (= 1004.0/287.0 - 1.0); the .esm `default` field is numeric, so the upstream defining expressions are evaluated at migration time. All eight parameters appear in the equations — Θ in three, P_0 in two, z in three, g and c_p in the H_s equation, R_d in the ρ_bar equation, inv_kappa in the p_bar equation, inv_kappa_m1 in the ρ_bar equation — so none is pruned (cf. the unused-parameter pruning applied in general_circulation.esm).\n\nVariable classification. T_bar, p_bar, ρ_bar, H_s are encoded `type: state` with no `default` — each is the LHS of exactly one purely-algebraic equation, an observed quantity with no time derivative and hence no initial condition, the convention used for the algebraic outputs of sibling diagnostic_pressure.esm and anelastic_thermo.esm. The Greek-named symbols Θ and ρ_bar are carried with their exact Unicode names, as the sibling anelastic_thermo.esm does for ρ_bar / dθ_dx.\n\nEquation faithfulness. The four upstream equations (src/clark1977.jl:77-80) are preserved verbatim: H_s ~ c_p*Θ/g (the isentropic scale height); T_bar ~ Θ*(1 - z/H_s) (Eq. 2.7); p_bar ~ P_0*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa (Eq. 2.8); ρ_bar ~ P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa_m1 (Eq. 2.9). Julia operator precedence is preserved in the op trees: `^` binds tighter than `*` and `/`, and `*`/`/` are left-associative — so `c_p*Θ/g` is `(c_p*Θ)/g` and `P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(...)^inv_kappa_m1` is `(P_0/(R_d*Θ))*((...)^inv_kappa_m1)`. The shared sub-expression (1 - z/H_s) is written out in each of the three height-dependent equations rather than introduced as a separate observed variable, mirroring the upstream source.\n\nUnits and dimensional consistency. The upstream declares g in u\"m/s^2\"; R_d and c_p in u\"J/(kg*K)\"; Θ and T_bar in u\"K\"; P_0 and p_bar in u\"Pa\"; z and H_s in u\"m\"; ρ_bar in u\"kg/m^3\"; inv_kappa and inv_kappa_m1 are dimensionless (recorded as units \"1\"). All are carried verbatim. Unlike the sibling DiagnosticPressure component, the upstream uses a plain `System(eqs, t; name)` with no `checks = false`: the four equations are dimensionally consistent — H_s ~ c_p*Θ/g is (J/(kg*K))*K/(m/s^2) = (m^2/s^2)/(m/s^2) = m; the z/H_s ratio is dimensionless, so T_bar ~ Θ*(1-z/H_s) is K and p_bar ~ P_0*(...)^inv_kappa is Pa; ρ_bar ~ P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(...)^inv_kappa_m1 is Pa/(J/kg) = (kg/(m*s^2))/(m^2/s^2) = kg/m^3.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6, abs=1e-9). The system is a closed-form algebraic evaluation — no ODE integration, no implicit solve — so there is no integrator error to bound. rel=1e-6 covers float64 round-off in the multiply/divide chains and, in particular, the `pow` evaluations of the (1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa and ^inv_kappa_m1 terms, where the migration's op-tree order and the canonical runner's evaluation may differ by a few ULP; it matches the sibling explicit-algebraic components. abs=1e-9 is a floor for the assertions; every output in the test suite is an O(1)-or-larger physical quantity (densities ~0.43-1.39 kg/m^3, temperatures ~202-320 K, pressures ~2.5e4-1e5 Pa, scale heights ~2.6e4-3.3e4 m), so the relative tolerance governs every comparison.\n\nTest reproduction. The upstream package provides four testsets touching this component (test/clark1977_test.jl): `Structure` (a System with 4 unknowns and 4 equations); `Surface Values` (T_bar=300, p_bar=1e5, ρ_bar=1e5/(287*300), H_s=1004*300/9.81 at the defaults); `Profile` (the z=5000 m profile, with T_bar<300 and p_bar<1e5); `Hydrostatic Balance` (the finite-difference dp/dz between z=0 and z=100 m equals -ρ̄g to rtol 1e-3); and `Isentropic Scale Height Validation` (H_s ≈ 30683 m to 1%). The eight inline tests here reproduce all of these — surface_values exercises all four outputs at the defaults (covering Structure, Surface Values and the scale-height validation); hydrostatic_balance_100m pins the z=100 m profile (the upstream finite-difference check dp/dz ≈ -ρ̄g is satisfied by the surface_values and hydrostatic_balance_100m pressures and densities to a relative error of 3.3e-6); profile_at_5km reproduces the Profile testset — and add coverage the upstream suite lacks: upper_troposphere_10km (a higher-altitude profile, all three profiles monotonically decreasing); warm_potential_temperature and cold_potential_temperature (the scale height H_s = c_p*Θ/g and the surface temperature T_bar(0) = Θ both scale with the reference potential temperature); elevated_surface_pressure (p_bar and ρ_bar scale linearly with P_0 while H_s is independent of it); and combined_profile (all three free parameters off their defaults, sampled at t=0 and t=1 to confirm the algebraic system is time-invariant). Every `expected` value is the IEEE-754 double produced by evaluating the four equations in float64 at the test's parameter set — equivalently the value the canonical ESS runner computes."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6,
                "abs": 1.0e-9
            },
            "variables": {
                "g": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s^2",
                    "default": 9.81,
                    "description": "Gravitational acceleration. Upstream @constant carried as a fixed-default parameter."
                },
                "R_d": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(kg*K)",
                    "default": 287.0,
                    "description": "Dry-air gas constant. Upstream @constant carried as a fixed-default parameter."
                },
                "c_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(kg*K)",
                    "default": 1004.0,
                    "description": "Specific heat of dry air at constant pressure. Upstream @constant carried as a fixed-default parameter."
                },
                "inv_kappa": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 3.4982578397212545,
                    "description": "Pressure-profile exponent c_p/R_d = 1/κ (dimensionless). Derived upstream @constant inv_kappa = c_p/R_d; the default is the evaluated value 1004.0/287.0."
                },
                "inv_kappa_m1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 2.4982578397212545,
                    "description": "Density-profile exponent c_p/R_d - 1 (dimensionless). Derived upstream @constant inv_kappa_m1 = c_p/R_d - 1.0; the default is the evaluated value 1004.0/287.0 - 1.0."
                },
                "Θ": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 300.0,
                    "description": "Reference potential temperature of the isentropic base state (constant with height, Clark 1977 Eq. 2.6)."
                },
                "P_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 100000.0,
                    "description": "Surface (z = 0) pressure of the base-state atmosphere."
                },
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Height above the surface at which the base-state profiles are evaluated."
                },
                "T_bar": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "K",
                    "description": "Base-state temperature T_bar = Θ*(1 - z/H_s) (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.7). An observed (algebraic) output — the LHS of one purely-algebraic equation, with no time derivative and hence no initial condition. Falls linearly with height."
                },
                "p_bar": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "description": "Base-state pressure p_bar = P_0*(1 - z/H_s)^(c_p/R_d) (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.8). An observed (algebraic) output; no time derivative, no initial condition. Falls as a power of (1 - z/H_s) with height."
                },
                "ρ_bar": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "description": "Base-state (anelastic reference) air density ρ_bar = P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(1 - z/H_s)^(c_p/R_d - 1) (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.9). An observed (algebraic) output; no time derivative, no initial condition."
                },
                "H_s": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Isentropic scale height H_s = c_p*Θ/g — the depth of the isentropic atmosphere, at which the base-state temperature, pressure and density reach zero. An observed (algebraic) output; depends only on the reference potential temperature Θ."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "_comment": "Isentropic scale height H_s = c_p*Θ/g (Clark 1977 Sec. 2) — the e-folding-like depth that sets the vertical structure of the base-state profiles.",
                    "lhs": "H_s",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            { "op": "*", "args": ["c_p", "Θ"] },
                            "g"
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Clark 1977 Eq. 2.7 — base-state temperature T_bar = Θ*(1 - z/H_s); linear decrease with height.",
                    "lhs": "T_bar",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "Θ",
                            {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [1, { "op": "/", "args": ["z", "H_s"] }]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Clark 1977 Eq. 2.8 — base-state pressure p_bar = P_0*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa, with inv_kappa = c_p/R_d.",
                    "lhs": "p_bar",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "P_0",
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [1, { "op": "/", "args": ["z", "H_s"] }]
                                    },
                                    "inv_kappa"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Clark 1977 Eq. 2.9 — base-state density ρ_bar = P_0/(R_d*Θ)*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa_m1, with inv_kappa_m1 = c_p/R_d - 1.",
                    "lhs": "ρ_bar",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "/",
                                "args": ["P_0", { "op": "*", "args": ["R_d", "Θ"] }]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [1, { "op": "/", "args": ["z", "H_s"] }]
                                    },
                                    "inv_kappa_m1"
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "surface_values",
                    "description": "All parameters at their declared defaults (Θ = 300 K, P_0 = 1e5 Pa, z = 0). At the surface (1 - z/H_s) = 1, so T_bar = Θ = 300 K and p_bar = P_0 = 1e5 Pa exactly; ρ_bar = P_0/(R_d*Θ) = 1e5/(287*300) = 1.1614401858304297 kg/m^3 (the surface ideal-gas density); H_s = c_p*Θ/g = 1004*300/9.81 = 30703.363914373087 m. Exercises all four outputs at once — reproduces the upstream `Structure` (4 unknowns, 4 equations), `Surface Values`, and `Isentropic Scale Height Validation` (H_s ≈ 30683 m to 1%) testsets.",
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 300.0 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 100000.0 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.1614401858304297 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30703.363914373087 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "hydrostatic_balance_100m",
                    "description": "Base-state profile 100 m above the surface (z = 100, all other parameters default). T_bar = 300*(1 - 100/H_s) = 299.0229083665339 K, p_bar = 1e5*(1 - 100/H_s)^inv_kappa = 98865.25504023193 Pa, ρ_bar = 1e5/(287*300)*(1 - 100/H_s)^inv_kappa_m1 = 1.1520128756692036 kg/m^3; H_s = 30703.363914373087 m is unchanged (independent of z). Reproduces the z = 100 m point of the upstream `Hydrostatic Balance` testset: with the surface_values pressures and densities, the finite-difference (p_bar(100) - p_bar(0))/100 = -11.347 Pa/m matches -ρ̄*g (ρ̄ the 0-100 m mean density) to a relative error of 3.3e-6.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "z": 100.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 299.0229083665339 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 98865.25504023193 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.1520128756692036 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30703.363914373087 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "profile_at_5km",
                    "description": "Base-state profile at z = 5000 m (mid-troposphere), all other parameters default. (1 - z/H_s) = 0.8371... gives T_bar = 251.14541832669323 K (< 300 K), p_bar = 53696.81236367263 Pa (< 1e5 Pa), ρ_bar = 0.7449743994418361 kg/m^3; H_s = 30703.363914373087 m. Reproduces the upstream `Profile` testset, including its T_bar < 300 and p_bar < 1e5 checks.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "z": 5000.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 251.14541832669323 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 53696.81236367263 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.7449743994418361 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30703.363914373087 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upper_troposphere_10km",
                    "description": "Base-state profile at z = 10000 m (upper troposphere), all other parameters default. (1 - z/H_s) = 0.6743... gives T_bar = 202.29083665338644 K, p_bar = 25193.61612123406 Pa, ρ_bar = 0.43394271347629165 kg/m^3 — all three profiles continue their monotonic decrease with height; H_s = 30703.363914373087 m. Confirms the profiles stay positive and well-behaved at large height fractions z/H_s (here 0.326).",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "z": 10000.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 202.29083665338644 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 25193.61612123406 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.43394271347629165 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30703.363914373087 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "warm_potential_temperature",
                    "description": "Warmer base state Θ = 320 K at the surface (z = 0). The scale height grows with Θ: H_s = c_p*Θ/g = 1004*320/9.81 = 32750.25484199796 m. At the surface T_bar = Θ = 320 K and p_bar = P_0 = 1e5 Pa; the surface density falls with Θ, ρ_bar = 1e5/(287*320) = 1.088850174216028 kg/m^3. Isolates the Θ-dependence of the scale height and the surface temperature.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "Θ": 320.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 320.0 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 100000.0 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.088850174216028 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 32750.25484199796 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "cold_potential_temperature",
                    "description": "Colder base state Θ = 250 K at the surface (z = 0). The scale height shrinks with Θ: H_s = c_p*Θ/g = 1004*250/9.81 = 25586.136595310905 m. At the surface T_bar = Θ = 250 K and p_bar = P_0 = 1e5 Pa; the surface density rises with the colder base state, ρ_bar = 1e5/(287*250) = 1.3937282229965158 kg/m^3. Together with warm_potential_temperature this brackets the linear H_s = c_p*Θ/g relation.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "Θ": 250.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 250.0 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 100000.0 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.3937282229965158 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 25586.136595310905 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "elevated_surface_pressure",
                    "description": "Higher surface pressure P_0 = 1.05e5 Pa evaluated at z = 2000 m (Θ default). Pressure and density scale linearly with P_0: p_bar = 1.05e5*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa = 82957.22050236931 Pa and ρ_bar = 1.05e5/(287*300)*(1 - z/H_s)^inv_kappa_m1 = 1.0306333794442013 kg/m^3. T_bar = 280.45816733067727 K and H_s = 30703.363914373087 m are independent of P_0. Confirms the P_0 prefactor of Eqs. 2.8-2.9 and the P_0-independence of the temperature profile and scale height.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "P_0": 105000.0, "z": 2000.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 280.45816733067727 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 82957.22050236931 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0306333794442013 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30703.363914373087 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "combined_profile",
                    "description": "All three free parameters off their defaults at once: Θ = 290 K, P_0 = 9.5e4 Pa, z = 3000 m. H_s = c_p*290/g = 29679.91845056065 m; T_bar = 290*(1 - 3000/H_s) = 260.68725099601596 K; p_bar = 9.5e4*(1 - 3000/H_s)^inv_kappa = 65438.0742158486 Pa; ρ_bar = 9.5e4/(287*290)*(1 - 3000/H_s)^inv_kappa_m1 = 0.8746389643596594 kg/m^3. Sampled at t = 0 and t = 1 to confirm the algebraic system is time-invariant.",
                    "parameter_overrides": { "Θ": 290.0, "P_0": 95000.0, "z": 3000.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 260.68725099601596 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 65438.0742158486 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.8746389643596594 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 0.0, "expected": 29679.91845056065 },
                        { "variable": "T_bar", "time": 1.0, "expected": 260.68725099601596 },
                        { "variable": "p_bar", "time": 1.0, "expected": 65438.0742158486 },
                        { "variable": "ρ_bar", "time": 1.0, "expected": 0.8746389643596594 },
                        { "variable": "H_s", "time": 1.0, "expected": 29679.91845056065 }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "base_state_vertical_profile",
                    "description": "The three base-state thermodynamic profiles — temperature T_bar (Eq. 2.7), pressure p_bar (Eq. 2.8) and density ρ_bar (Eq. 2.9) — as functions of height z from the surface to 15 km, at the default isentropic base state (Θ = 300 K, P_0 = 1e5 Pa). Temperature falls linearly with height; pressure and density fall as powers of the same (1 - z/H_s) factor. This is the canonical vertical structure of the Clark (1977) isentropic reference atmosphere.",
                    "initial_state": { "type": "per_variable", "values": {} },
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "z",
                                "range": { "start": 0.0, "stop": 15000.0, "count": 31, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "temperature_profile",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Base-state temperature T_bar vs height (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.7).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Height above surface z (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "T_bar", "label": "Base-state temperature T_bar (K)" }
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "pressure_profile",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Base-state pressure p_bar vs height (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.8).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Height above surface z (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "p_bar", "label": "Base-state pressure p_bar (Pa)" }
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "density_profile",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Base-state density ρ_bar vs height (Clark 1977 Eq. 2.9).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Height above surface z (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "ρ_bar", "label": "Base-state density ρ_bar (kg/m^3)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "scale_height_vs_potential_temperature",
                    "description": "Isentropic scale height H_s = c_p*Θ/g as a function of the reference potential temperature Θ swept from 250 to 400 K. H_s is linear in Θ and independent of the surface pressure and height — a warmer isentropic atmosphere is deeper.",
                    "initial_state": { "type": "per_variable", "values": {} },
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "Θ",
                                "range": { "start": 250.0, "stop": 400.0, "count": 31, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "H_s_vs_theta",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Isentropic scale height H_s as a function of reference potential temperature Θ.",
                            "x": { "variable": "Θ", "label": "Reference potential temperature Θ (K)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "H_s", "label": "Isentropic scale height H_s (m)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "surface_density_vs_potential_temperature",
                    "description": "Surface (z = 0) base-state density ρ_bar as a function of the reference potential temperature Θ swept from 250 to 400 K, at the default surface pressure P_0 = 1e5 Pa. At the surface (1 - z/H_s) = 1, so Eq. 2.9 reduces to the ideal-gas relation ρ_bar = P_0/(R_d*Θ): density is inversely proportional to the potential temperature.",
                    "initial_state": { "type": "per_variable", "values": {} },
                    "parameters": { "z": 0.0 },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "Θ",
                                "range": { "start": 250.0, "stop": 400.0, "count": 31, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "rho_bar_surface_vs_theta",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Surface base-state density ρ_bar as a function of reference potential temperature Θ (the ideal-gas limit of Eq. 2.9 at z = 0).",
                            "x": { "variable": "Θ", "label": "Reference potential temperature Θ (K)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "ρ_bar", "label": "Surface base-state density ρ_bar (kg/m^3)" }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
